<Document>
<name>Cherohala Skyway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Cherohala Skyway</h2><p><i>Tennessee / North Carolina, USA · TN-165 / NC-143, Tellico Plains TN to Robbinsville NC</i></p><p><b>67 km of high-elevation byway across the spine of the Unicoi Mountains.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>49 km (30 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>1.5–2 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Bears, motorcyclists at speed, fog, no fuel between endpoints</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>101</td></tr></table><hr><p>A relatively new road (1996) built specifically as a scenic byway, running along ridgetops between 1,200 and 1,600 m. Twin to its better-known cousin Tail of the Dragon (US-129), which is just down the road on the north side of Lake Santeetlah. The name combines Cherokee and Nantahala National Forests. No commercial traffic, very few houses, and a switchback ascent on each end with a long ridge run in the middle. Joyce Kilmer Memorial Forest, just off the eastern end, is one of the few accessible old-growth forests left in the Southern Appalachians — tulip poplars 400+ years old.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Indian Boundary Lake</b> — Small mountain lake with a 5 km loop trail, swimming beach, and rentable cabins. Eagles and herons regular.</li><li><b>Turkey Creek overlook</b> — 1,646 m. Long view back into Tennessee — on clear days you can see the lower Smokies.</li><li><b>Big Junction</b> — Highest point (1,643 m). Open balds with summer wildflowers — Catawba rhododendron in June.</li><li><b>Joyce Kilmer Memorial Forest (spur)</b> — Old-growth tulip poplars and hemlocks, some 400+ years old, in a 15 km² roadless tract. 3 km figure-eight loop.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
